<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="86" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="20.[130,646,163,1730]" box="[130,254,300,326]" pageId="20" pageNumber="86">
<emphasis box="[130,254,300,326]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="86">Comments</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[130,646,163,1730]" pageId="20" pageNumber="86">
This species was captured in abundance at the Tabalar, Marang and Tintang forma- tions, and was captured emerging from 
<collectingRegion box="[130,179,436,462]" country="India" name="Goa" pageId="20" pageNumber="86">Gua</collectingRegion>
Mat at Tabalar and roosting in 
<collectingRegion box="[596,645,436,462]" country="India" name="Goa" pageId="20" pageNumber="86">Gua</collectingRegion>
Bandung at Tintang. It is easily identified by its bluntly pointed connecting process, size and distinct coloration (the noseleaf is brown-orange). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1861" box="[357,645,572,598]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="86" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="borneensis">
<emphasis box="[357,645,572,598]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="86">Rhinolophus borneensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is considered widespread and common throughout Borneo where there are cave systems (
<bibRefCitation accessDate="2006-12-20" author="BOITANI, L. &amp; G. CATULLO &amp; I. MARZETTI &amp; M. MASI &amp; M. RULLI &amp; S. SAVINI" box="[237,466,675,702]" journalOrPublisher="Istituto di Ecologia Applicata, Rome" pageId="20" pageNumber="86" publicationUrl="http://www.ieaitaly.org/samd/" refId="ref17487" refString="BOITANI, L., G. CATULLO, I. MARZETTI, M. MASI, M. RULLI, and S. SAVINI. 2006. The Southeast Asian Mammal Databank. A tool for conservation and monitoring of mammal diversity in Southeast Asia. Istituto di Ecologia Applicata, Rome. http: // www. ieaitaly. org / samd / (last accessed 20 December 2006)." title="The Southeast Asian Mammal Databank. A tool for conservation and monitoring of mammal diversity in Southeast Asia" type="url" year="2006">
Boitani 
<emphasis box="[332,383,675,701]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="86">et al</emphasis>
., 2006
</bibRefCitation>
), but it has also been recorded in Barito Ulu and Sungai Wain, where there are no known cave sys- tems for over 
<quantity box="[296,374,777,803]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="20" pageNumber="86" unit="km" value="20.0">20 km</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
